ce:section.ce:para:
According to the experimental results, a possible mechanism was presented for the separation of electrons and holes and improving photocatalytic performance in the CMSCN5 composite under solar radiation (Fig. 7
                        ). The blue trace in Fig. 6 shows the reaction process of photocatalytic H2 evolution from the D-MoS2/p-C3N5 composite system. The polymer semiconductor p-C3N5 absorbs photon energy from solar radiation and excites electron-hole pairs, but the electrons and holes readily recombine with low activity. After the introduction of the D-MoS2 cocatalyst, a tight interface is formed between D-MoS2 and p-C3N5 when the CMSCN photocatalyst is calcined, and the formation of this heterogeneous structure can enhance the separation efficiency of photocarriers with rapid electron migration. The above experimental results indicate that the CB and VB edge potentials of composite CMSCN5 are determined to be −0.34 and + 1.39 eV, respectively. The CB edge potential of p-C3N5 is more negative than that of MoS2, which allows electron transfer from the CB of p-C3N5 to MoS2. In the CMSCN system, the mobile photoinduced electrons in the CB of p-C3N5 transfer to the MoS2 cocatalyst through the contact interface, which promotes the separation of electron-hole pairs. The CDs are attached to MoS2 as electron acceptors, which can effectively facilitate charge transfer efficiency and synergistically improve the photocatalytic performance. The electrons are collected and stored by CD particles, transferred to MoS2 nanosheets, interact with H+ adsorbed at the MoS2 edges and evolve H2, and the h+ in the VB of p-C3N5 is consumed by S2- and SO3
                        2-. As a result, the recombination process of photocarriers is markedly suppressed, leading to a significant increase in H2 yield of the CMSN5 photocatalyst.
